## Where the role-based UI plan actually stands

The plan (approved and in progress) has four phases. Only the first is underway, and it is backend authorization work, not UI:

| Phase | Status | What it covers |
|---|---|---|
| **Phase 1 — RBAC hardening** | **Implemented, tested, not yet committed** | Backend-only. Fail-closed authorization, mandatory JWT signature verification, service-to-service auth, inbound webhook signature checks. No UI. |
| **Phase 2 — Borrower/Vendor CIAM (Ory Kratos + Hydra)** | **Not started** | Would let vendors actually log in (today `/vendors/*` and `/loans/*` are fully open, no identity binding). This is the prerequisite for the external `project-k-borrower-app` PWA to have real auth. |
| **Phase 3 — Platform Console** (new repo, ops + admin + lender views) | **Not started** | The actual UI surface for ops staff, admins, and lender analysts. No repo has been created yet. |
| **Phase 4 — Anchor Portal** | **Deferred by design** | No screens planned yet; only groundwork so it can be added later without rework. |

### Why Phase 1 had to come first

Every later UI phase assumes a trustworthy authorization layer. Before building a login screen or a Platform Console, the plan fixes the RBAC gaps found during investigation (fail-open defaults, a JWT verification path that silently fell back to unverified decoding, three internal services with zero auth, DPDP rights/consent endpoints reachable by anyone). None of that is visual — it's the plumbing a real UI would plug into.

